'''Sumikomorida Kofun''' (墨小盛田古墳, also pronounced as Sumiko Morita Kofun<ref name=Shisui>{{Cite web|和書|author=Shisui Town Hall|url=https://www.town.shisui.chiba.jp/navi/mobile/id/374.html|title=Sumikomorida Kofun|work=Shisui Tourism Navi|accessdate=2020-08-20}}</ref>) is a {{ill|Square Kofun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Shisui, Chiba|ja|酒々井町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan.

== Overview ==
The Kofun measures approximately 30 meters north-south, 23 meters east-west, and 3 meters in height. {{ill|Rectangular Kofun|lt=Rectangular Kofuns|ja|長方形墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are a characteristic type of kofun found in the {{ill|Shimousa Province|ja|下総国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} region during the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name=Shisui/>

In November 1986, during the construction of the {{ill|Shisui Comprehensive Park|ja|酒々井総合公園|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a one-month excavation was conducted. The mound features a 2-meter-wide surrounding moat and a protruding section. The main burial chamber, located at the center of the southern side of the mound, was identified as a {{ill|horizontal stone burial chamber|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Based on the {{ill|sue ware|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|qq=draft|qq=draft}} found on the terrace section, the kofun is believed to have been constructed in the late 7th to early 8th century. Restoration work was carried out in February 1987.

